7. Calculate power as $P = I \times S^2$ where P is power, I is intensity, and S is spot size. Convert this value into a desired unit (e.g., watts) if necessary. Ensure that the generated powers fall within realistic ranges according to provided univariate statistics.

For simplicity, we can use a linear regression model between energy and cutoff\_energy (with Pearson coefficient 0.672) as a starting point.
